5.\n\nrathira, charioteer, III, 1, 17; 26, 1.\n\nrathi\xc2\xb4, drawing a chariot: a _s_ vasa _h_ rathya _h_ , I, 148, 3; III, 6,\n8;--charioteer, I, 77, 3; III, 3, 6; IV, 15, 2; rathi\xc2\xb4 _h_ adhvara\xc2\xb4 _n_ am, I,\n44, 2; rathi\xc2\xb4 _h_ _ri_ tasya, III, 2, 8; IV, 10, 2.\n\nrathya, of a chariot: atya _h_ rathya _h_ , II, 4, 4; rathya-iva (supply _k_\nakra\xc2\xb4?), II, 4, 6:2; _k_ akram rathya-iva (rather rathyam-iva?), IV, I, 3:1.\n\nrad, to cleave: ratsi, V, 10, 1.\n\nradhra: radhrasya for adhrasya, (I, 31, 14:2).\n\nrapas: rapa _m_ si, Pada text instead of apa _m_ si, I, 69, 8:2.\n\nrabh: sam rebhire, they have embraced, I, 140, 8;--abhi sam rabhante, they\ntake care of, III, 29, 13.\n\np. 466\n\nrabhas, vigour, I. 145, 3.\n\nrabhasa, robust, II, 10, 4:1; fierce, III, 1, 8.\n\nram-su, joyously, II, 4, 5.\n\nram-su _g_ ihva, with lovely tongue, IV, 1, 8.\n\nrayi, riches, treasures: kshapa\xc2\xb4-van rayi _n_ a\xc2\xb4m, I, 70, 5:1.\n\nrayi-pati, treasure-lord: rayi-pati _h_ rayi _n_ a\xc2\xb4m, I, 60, 4; 72, 1; II, 9,\n4.\n\nrayi-vid, gainer of wealth, II, 1, 3; III, 7, 3.\n\nrayisha\xc2\xb4h, conqueror of wealth, I, 58, 3.\n\nrava, shouting, roaring, I, 71, 2; 94, 10; agne rave _n_ a (Pada: agne _h_\navena), I, 128, 5:1.\n\nra _s_ ana\xc2\xb4, rope, (I, 13, 11:1); IV, 1, 9:2; V, 1, 3:1.\n\nra _s_ mi, ray, I, 59, 3; IV, 13, 4; 14, 2; 3; V, 19, 5;--sapta ra _s_ maya\n_h_ , seven rays or reins, II, 5, 2;--rein, I, 141, 11; III, 7, 9:1; _ri_\ntasya ra _s_ mim, V, 7, 3.\n\nrasa, sap, I, 71, 5:1.\n\nRahuga _n_ a, plur., the Rahuga _n_ as, I, 78, 5:1.\n\nra, to give: rasate, I, 96, 8; rarishe, II, 1, 5; rarima, II, 5, 7; rara _n_ a\n_h_ , a liberal giver, III, 1, 22; IV, 1, 5; 2, 10.\n\nra _g_ , to be king or lord: ra\xc2\xb4 _g_ antam adhvara\xc2\xb4 _n_ am, I, 1, 8; 45, 4; ra\n_g_ asi, I, 36, 12; 188, 1; ra _g_ an (conj. ra\xc2\xb4 _g_ an), 1, 79, 6:1;--vira\xc2\xb4\n_g_ atha, I, 188, 4;--adhi vira\xc2\xb4 _g_ ata _h_ , you reign high, I, 188, 6:1.\n\nra